The introduction of them into the story is almost the only blemish of that exquisite pices, and we have still less pleasure in seeing their portraits. How different from Hogarth’s terrible pictures of the same miserable class! There you see the truth 3 you can imagine the past and the future, as well as perceive the present. Beauty, grace, often tenderness, sinking into ruin under the steady influence of a life of sin, make them objects at once of our profoundest compassion-—and of our instant reprobation.
